textAfterTable: frostweed Josephine, Arlington, TX (Zone 8a) August 12, 2012 8:50 AM Post #9238832 Good idea, here is another link; http://wildflower.org/plants/result.php?id_plant=CEOC jujubetexas San Marcos, TX (Zone 8b) August 15, 2012 7:24 AM Post #9242164 Just remember that once the Hackberry is large, you will have to pull about 500 Hackberry seedlings every spring to summer. Just sayin. By the way, Hackberries are edible. The thin outside tastes a little like hot cinnamon. The only decent Hackberries are the one with soft M&M seeds on the insides. If they are hard seeded, not worth it. You can even make a cookie dough type substance by smashing all the soft seeds with a mallet. jujubetexas San Marcos, TX (Zone 8b) August 15, 2012 7:25 AM Post #9242165 Hackberry trees are also know for breaking easily in storms. I had three 40 footers come down in one storm.
